e from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Monfort   1. This surname is most common in Brittany and Haute-Savoie. See also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Henry de Montfort was born about 1160, in Beaudesert, Warwickshire, England as the son of Lord Thurston De Montfort and Lady Juliane Beaudesert De Murdac. He married Emma Corbuceo in 1179, in Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1197, at the age of 38."},"et":{"about 1160–1197":"umbes 1160–1197","1153–1183":"1153–1183","1155–1202":"1155–1202","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1160–1197":"1160–1197","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1159–1190":"1159–1190","1184–1216":"1184–1216","1120–1190":"1120–1190","–Female":"Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","1164":"1164","1153":"1153","1184":"1184","1162":"1162","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1159":"1159","1158":"1158","1202":"1202","1179":"1179","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","Beaudesert, Henley In Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Beaudesert, Warwickshire, England","Wellesbourne Montfort, Warwickshire, , England":"Wellesbourne, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1160–1197":"noin 1160–1197","1153–1183":"1153–1183","1155–1202":"1155–1202","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","1160–1197":"1160–1197","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1159–1190":"1159–1190","1184–1216":"1184–1216","1120–1190":"1120–1190","–Female":"Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1160":"noin 1160","1197":"1197","1120":"1120","